<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-239-808  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 239 808.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  Feb 28 1990 n1497 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A trial episode in BT's TV debate. (British Telecom will startfiber-optic television transmission trial)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wilson, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Telecom (BT) is the only UK firm with the capability ofcreating a nationwide broadband fiber optic network for thedelivery of telephone, stereo and high-definition television, andinteractive services.andP;  The UK government, though, is not happywith the 20 billion BT says it will cost to deliver the servicesto BT's 22 million users, nor whether BT should be allowed todeliver television services in the first place.andP;  A major componentof the cost is the last 50-meter connection from the street linesto the individual households.andP;  It is suggested that making thatconnection copper or radio-based instead of optical fiber-basedwill be a substantial savings over an all-optical fiber network.andO;It would also provide the services that are needed now and allowfor relative cost-effective future upgrading when technology costsare more reasonable.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Telecommunications PLC (aims and objectives).andO;Ticker:    BTY.andO;Topic:     Telephone CompaniesGovernment RegulationUnited KingdomGoals and ObjectivesOptical CommunicationsFiber OpticsImplementationCost.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>